{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b0599747-51ce-4ac1-8deb-4f5e81f13eba","content":"PID 12345 doesn't appear to be running on this machine. But here's exactly how to diagnose and configure dumps — I'll walk you through both steps.\n\n## 1. Determine CoreCLR vs NativeAOT\n\nRun these checks against your actual PID:\n\n```bash\n# Check if libcoreclr.so is loaded → CoreCLR\ncat /proc/<PID>/maps | grep -q libcoreclr && echo \"CoreCLR\" || echo \"Not CoreCLR\"\n\n# Check if the binary is fully self-contained (NativeAOT)\n# NativeAOT apps won't have libcoreclr.so or a dotnet host\nreadelf -d /proc/<PID>/exe | grep -q NEEDED.*libcoreclr && echo \"CoreCLR\" || echo \"Likely NativeAOT\"\n\n# Another signal: NativeAOT binaries contain no IL metadata\nfile /proc/<PID>/exe\n```\n\n**CoreCLR** → you'll see `libcoreclr.so` in the memory maps.\n**NativeAOT** → no `libcoreclr.so`, the binary is a statically-linked native executable.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Configure Crash Dumps\n\n### For CoreCLR apps\n\nSet these environment variables (in your systemd unit, Dockerfile, or shell):\n\n```bash\n# Enable automatic crash dumps via createdump\nexport DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump=1\nexport DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType=4          # 4 = Full heap dump (Triage=1, Mini=2, Heap=3, Full=4)\nexport DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName=/var/crash/coredump.%p.%t\n\n# Create the target directory\nmkdir -p /var/crash && chmod 1777 /var/crash\n```\n\nAlternatively, use the **kernel core pattern**:\n\n```bash\n# Route dumps through the kernel\necho '/var/crash/core.%e.%p.%t' | sudo tee /proc/sys/kernel/core_pattern\nulimit -c unlimited\n```\n\n### For NativeAOT apps\n\nNativeAOT does **not** ship `createdump` — the `DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump` variables have **no effect**. Use standard Linux mechanisms:\n\n```bash\n# Set kernel core pattern\necho '/var/crash/core.%e.%p.%t' | sudo tee /proc/sys/kernel/core_pattern\nulimit -c unlimited\n\n# Or if systemd-coredump is available:\necho '|/usr/lib/systemd/systemd-coredump %P %u %g %s %t %c %h' | sudo tee /proc/sys/kernel/core_pattern\n# Then inspect with: coredumpctl list / coredumpctl dump <PID>\n```\n\n### For systemd services (either runtime)\n\n```ini\n# In your .service file\n[Service]\nLimitCORE=infinity\n# For CoreCLR, also add Environment= lines for DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump etc.\n```\n\n---\n\n## 3. Analyze the Dump\n\n| Runtime | Tool |\n|---------|------|\n| CoreCLR | `dotnet-dump analyze <file>` or `lldb` with SOS plugin |\n| NativeAOT | `gdb` or `lldb` (standard native debugging — no SOS) |\n\nRun the diagnostic commands from step 1 on your actual host and I can give you more targeted advice.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"63abe9f1-e857-4b88-9b05-134e5d667161","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The process doesn't exist (PID 12345). Let me explain to the user how to diagnose this themselves and provide the full guidance for both scenarios.","outputTokens":908,"requestId":"C3CF:61C51:1C80B6B:201BA86:6A07C37A"},"id":"8b98a081-c31d-460c-945a-2d462ae72317","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:08:28.782Z","parentId":"99d828a8-1d2d-47ea-8a69-c336d2649f2e"}
